In 1986, Eli Lilly and Gennentech produced Humulin, the first recombinant insulins to be approved for general medical use, by using a new technology called a proinsulin route. Proinsulin route produces a single chemically synthesized sequence for native human proinsulin. This method was preferred over a chain combination procedure because it was more efficient as it required only one fermentation and subsequent purification protocol.
